<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO PROFESSOR LOMBARDO</font><br>
<tt>Mon Feb 10 16:31:08 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Dear Professor Lombardo,<br><br>
Thank you for your e-mail message regarding your course on understanding violence. I would like to send a message to your students.<br><br>
I visited Song My (My Lai-4) with Vietnamese friends in April, 1993. The site is well tended and landscaped. There is a massive Socialist-style sculpture at the north end of the foot-path. In my perspective the sculpture does not convey the urgency and sadness of the site; that is accomplished by the compacted rectangles of earth that commemorate where the respective villagers lived... raised earthen rectangles with a simple stone monument giving the names of those murdered. <br><br>
Beyond the central statue to the east there is a low wall covered by a mosaic. This, too, does not convey the terror or horror of what took place here. <br><br>
That is accomplished by remembering the published photographs and walking to the respective sites: the ditch... the irrigation ditch that once was filled with bodies still lies to the east of the site. It was smaller than I had remembered; it flowed with clear irrigation water when I was there. the cotton tree.... below its branches long ago women and children huddled, pleading for their lives. The tree still grows although wounded by several bullet holes. These holes can be touched and if you insert your finger into the hole -- as I did -- .... the events at Song My become realized.  <br><br>
The museum at Song My is maintained by the government of Viet Nam; young women guides dressed in their au dais, explain the events to visitors in a variety of languages. Inside is a large, central meeting hall; the grand table is glass-covered. Visitors to Song My traditionally insert their personal business-professional cards under the glass, as tokens to define their presence.... then there are the photographs of the events. What strikes the visitor is that the American soldiers took photographs as they killed the villagers... photographic captions in the museum are not always correct... a press photograph of President Nixon is labeled incorrectly. One does not need a Who's Who, however, to know that took place at Song My.<br><br>
What struck me as a visitor to Song My most of all, however, were the villagers living and working outside the museum compound... they paused, smiled, and welcomed me, an American foreigner, as if I was their personal guest. The eyes of children; the eyes of the elderly....<br><br>
Survivors and relatives of those who experienced the terror... their hands stretched out in friendship and welcome.<br><br>
This is what I remember most from my visit to Song My; the two poles of human behavior anchored by shame and terror -- and human forgiveness and friendship.<br><br>
This is what I would tell you students who take your class on understanding violence, that act of violence is immediate, but the memory of violence lasts as long as there are people to remember.....<br><br>
Regards and best wishes to your students.
<p><code>-- legrivetti@ucdavis.edu  (louis e. grivetti) </code><p>


